\section{Caveat (important)}{

Phylogenetic signal is \emph{necessary but not sufficient} for good imputation.
A high-H² trait can still impute poorly under MNAR missingness; a low-H²
trait can still impute well if tightly coupled to an observed predictor.
The table sets expectations; it does not predict imputation performance.
}

\section{Base models}{

For each variable \code{v}, the function fits one univariate MCMCglmm with
\code{v ~ 1} as the fixed effect, and either \code{~Species} (single phylogenetic
random effect, \code{species = FALSE}) or \code{~Species + Species2} (dual random
effects: phylogenetic + non-phylogenetic species effect, \code{species = TRUE}).
The random-effect structure mirrors what BACE itself fits per variable, so
H² reported here is the same quantity BACE sees internally.

Priors follow \code{.make_prior()}: gaussian/poisson use
\code{R = list(V = 1, nu = 2)} and Gelman 2006 parameter-expanded G; threshold
(binary / ordered) uses \code{R = list(V = 1, fix = 1)}; multinomial uses
\code{R = list(V = (I + J)/K, fix = 1)} (Hadfield's IJ parameterization).
}

\section{MCMC defaults}{

If \code{nitt}/\code{burnin}/\code{thin} are \code{NULL}, type-specific defaults are used,
balanced to deliver 1500 post-burn draws with ESS > 1000 on every variance
component under typical data:\tabular{llll}{
   Type \tab nitt \tab burnin \tab thin \cr
   gaussian \tab 20000 \tab 5000 \tab 10 \cr
   poisson \tab 30000 \tab 7500 \tab 15 \cr
   binary / ordered \tab 50000 \tab 12500 \tab 25 \cr
   multinomial \tab 80000 \tab 20000 \tab 40 \cr
}


\code{quick = TRUE} halves nitt and burnin for a rough first-pass exploration
(post-burn draws ~750, ESS target ~500). Expect \code{low_ess} flags to trigger
more often in quick mode.
}

\section{Tree-size warnings}{

Defaults are calibrated for 50–500 species. Smaller trees make phylogenetic
variance weakly identifiable (H² pulled toward prior mean ~0.5; HPD very
wide); larger trees have slower per-iteration MCMC. The function emits
\code{small_tree} (n_species < 30) and \code{large_tree} (n_species > 1000) warnings
automatically, both attached to the returned object's \verb{$warnings} slot.
}

\section{Convergence diagnostics}{

Every fit is checked with \code{coda::effectiveSize()} and \code{coda::geweke.diag()}
on all non-fixed variance components. Rows with \code{min_ess < min_ess}
threshold are flagged \code{low_ess}; rows with any \verb{|z| > 2} are flagged
\code{geweke_fail}; either triggers \code{unreliable} in the \code{flag} column. Do not
interpret H² cells with either flag as data-driven estimates.
}

\section{H² formulas}{

With V_A = phylo variance, V_S = non-phylo species variance (dual RE
only), V_R = residual variance, the latent-scale H² formulas are:
\itemize{
\item gaussian / poisson single RE: V_A / (V_A + V_R)
\item gaussian / poisson dual RE:   V_A / (V_A + V_S + V_R)
\item threshold / ordered single:   V_A / (V_A + 1)
\item threshold / ordered dual:     V_A / (V_A + V_S + 1)
\item multinomial single RE:        tr(G_phylo) / (tr(G_phylo) + tr(R))
\item multinomial dual RE:          tr(G_phylo) / (tr(G_phylo) + tr(G_species) + tr(R))
}

References: de Villemereuil et al. 2016 \emph{Genetics} 204:1281; Nakagawa &
Schielzeth 2013 \emph{Methods Ecol Evol} 4:133; Hadfield & Nakagawa 2010
\emph{J Evol Biol} 23:494; Lynch 1991 \emph{Evolution} 45:1065.
}

\section{Multinomial}{
 H² versus lambda_nominal:
For \code{categorical} traits the table reports BOTH \verb{H2_*} and
\verb{lambda_nominal_*}. They measure related but DIFFERENT quantities and
typically disagree by 0.1-0.2 — that gap is expected, not a bug.
\itemize{
\item \code{H2_mean} is trace-based on MCMCglmm's working scale: residuals
take their MCMCglmm-reported diagonal \code{2/(J+1)} per non-baseline
level, with no rescaling. Faithful to the model's own variance
decomposition; useful for within-categorical reporting.
\item \code{lambda_nominal_mean} applies the Hadfield (2010 §3.7) / Amemiya
(1981) c² correction to put each level on the standard probit
scale (residual = 1 per level), then averages
\verb{lambda_k = G'_kk / (G'_kk + 1)} with
\verb{G'_kk = G_phylo[k,k] / (1 + c²·2/(J+1))}. This is the
Pagel-comparable statistic — same scale and interpretation as
Pagel's lambda for continuous traits, so it can be compared
across trait types in a multi-trait phylo_signal table.
}

Use \code{lambda_nominal_mean} for cross-trait comparisons; use
\code{H2_mean} when you specifically want MCMCglmm-native variance
partitioning. Per-level (one value per non-baseline category)
detail is on \code{attr(model, "lambda_nominal_per_level")} after a
run with \code{keep_models = TRUE}. Reference: Ayumi (2024)
multinomial GLMM tutorial,
\url{https://ayumi-495.github.io/multinomial-GLMM-tutorial/#nominal}.
}

